     OBJECTVISION NOW CONNECTS TO DB2 AND OTHER SQL SERVERS

     SCOTTS VALLEY, Calif. -- February 20, 1992 -- Borland

International Inc. (NASDAQ:BORL) today announced the availability

of its new ObjectVision SQL Connection.

     ObjectVision SQL Connection is an add-on product that allows

users to access DB2, IBM Corporation's mainframe database

management system, via the MDI (Micro Decisionware) gateway, and

directly connect to SQL Server and Sybase SQL data (on any

platform) transparently from an ObjectVision Windows application.

     The SQL Connection allows users to directly access SQL data

and reach important back-end, server-based data, without having

to know the SQL language.

     "With ObjectVision SQL, Borland has taken a good forms

metaphor and then expanded on it to make it a powerful end-user

development tool," said Mark Tebbe, president of Chicago-based

Lante Corporation, a management consulting firm. "ObjectVision

SQL is a natural extension to ObjectVision and is a unique

development package with an even stronger tie into the corporate

marketplace."

     With SQL Connection, users now have a broader range of data

connectivity and application development. SQL Connection allows

these users to connect SQL data with information from Paradox,

dBASE and Btrieve files within ObjectVision applications. Thus,

applications can have multiple, completely updatable access to

standard PC database files and SQL-based information.

