     The ObjectVision SQL Connection also supports flexible,

relational database structures, such as master-detail

relationships, between databases.

     "We developed ObjectVision SQL Connection in response to the

demand from our large installed base and corporate customers,"

said Gene Wang, vice president and general manager of Borland's

Languages Business Unit. "Users want easy application development

and broad, direct data connectivity to a variety of data sources.

And now we provide the easiest way to create Windows applications

that connect seamlessly to SQL information.

ObjectVision SQL Connection Background

     The SQL Connection is a Dynamic Link Library (DLL) that

self-registers to ObjectVision 2.0 applications. The Connection

provides the user with 20 database functions to connect and

manipulate database records without the user needing to know or

use SQL calls.

     The 20 new functions allow the user to log on and off the

SQL database, open SQL links to the database, scroll forward and

backward through the data, insert new records, modify records,

and delete records. Users can also locate records in the

database, and execute SQL statements they write.

     As with ObjectVision, the SQL Connection product includes a

single developer's license and unlimited, royalty-free Runtime.

A user can create ObjectVision SQL-based applications and freely

distribute them to other users or customers.

     "ObjectVision SQL Connection is also setting a new standard

in SQL product pricing by not charging a Runtime fee," added

Wang.

Application Development

     Since its initial launch in February, ObjectVision has

become one of the fastest selling Windows products on the market

because it provides the easiest way to create Windows

applications.

     ObjectVision enables non-technical computer users and

application developers to easily create business applications for

Windows without using a programming language. Applications

consist of three fundamental design elements: the user interface,

logic and links to databases.

