     Once created, these applications can be connected directly

to corporate data in popular database formats, such as Paradox,

dBASE or Btrieve files. ObjectVision also supports Dynamic Data

Exchange (DDE) to other Windows applications.

     "Borland is taking ObjectVision in the right direction by

empowering the user. Competitors' end-user products can access

SQL, but one cannot build applications with them, so they quickly

become very limited," said Dennis Clark, Technical Consultant,

Marathon Systems, a Santa Cruz-based developer of complete

information solutions. "ObjectVision is the easiest way to create

an SQL application, and in the end-user category, it's the most

powerful tool I've seen."

Security

     ObjectVision SQL Connection provides complete security to

users from the host SQL server and ObjectVision application files

can be password protected to prevent modification.

Pricing and Availability

     ObjectVision SQL Connection will be available directly from

Borland and will be distributed by retail outlets in the U.S. and

Canada. The ObjectVision SQL Connection has a suggested retail

price of $795 (which includes a license to make an unlimited

number of duplicate copies of the Runtime version) and is

scheduled to ship this month. (All prices are in U.S. dollars,

actual prices may vary at individual stores.)
